          "title": "Job 6 in canonical perspective — suffering, friendship, and God's silence",
          "body": "Job 6 sits at the intersection of three canonical threads. First, the theology of lament: the Psalms routinely sanction speech that is raw, proportionate to actual pain, and addressed directly to God (Psalms 22, 38, 88). Job's speech here is not heterodox — it is within the OT's established tradition of honest address to the divine. Second, the theology of friendship: the New Testament will ground Christian fellowship in a chesed that costs something (John 15:13; 1 John 3:16-17). The friends' wadi-failure in Job 6 is the negative image of what genuine covenant community looks like. Third, the theology of unanswered prayer: Job asks for death and God neither grants it nor responds. The silence of God is itself a theological statement — the restraint of the divine hand in chapters 1-2 becomes the silence of the divine voice through the dialogue. D.A. Carson's treatment in *How Long, O Lord?* is instructive here: God's silence is not God's absence, and Job's continued addressing of Him through the silence is itself an act of faith. The friends, by contrast, speak loudly and say nothing true. God will say so in Job 42:7."
